41 SERVUS PUBLICUS those prisoners of war who were not sold by the state were retained in its service as servi publici,- or they were bought by the state or bequeathed to it. Their condi· tion was better than that of private slaves, they were able to save money and had free quarters found them by the censors. They served the magistrates as assistants to the accensi and apparitores, were employed in the census, in prisons, at executions, at sacri- fices, in quarries, mines, waterworks etc.; they bought and sold on behalf of the state.
